description: Dimensions: EL 43mm; maxEW 27.2mm; maxEB 20.2; maxTsep 10mm; wt 70.4 gms,Typology: butt prob. fairly square originally, top uncertain; 'U' shaped sep. section,Manufacture: rippling in sep. probably cast mouldings, at least in part - otherwide hammer marks; distortion of mould valves evident for one side, rev. in line; blow hole in break,Condition: main break anc. - of one fg. broken also, butt corner uncertain,Attached Material: little orange staining.

collection: TRILL, Mr. E. - private no.3,(3),Pine Lodge, Fairley Park, Ringwood, Hants
surface: few small areas of grey-green p; rest flaked/pocked to pale & light green dry sur.,ATTACHED MATERIAL: patches of orange to buff soil staining
description: TYPOLOGY:elongated hexagonal bl. section; remains of fine rib emphasising blade angle - bordering of original internal ribs - but not certainly lower; int. ribs diverge with bl. & almost certainly short; rev. dec. uncertain, but v. faint hints of sim. ribs,MANUFACTURE: two low bumps on side prob. remains of eg. fl. rather then broken loop; one or two medium blow-holes in bullen surfaces,CONDITION: two major breaks ancient; rest prob. substantially intact except sur.
remarks: PIF,AFI,SI,CI,DF: S,Rec.: Sn. July 79,Source: Sb. A.,Sub. Inf.: P. Saunders - Salisbury Mus.

collection: Trill, Mr. E - private No. 1,Pine Lodge, Fairley Park, Ringwood, Hants
surface: Patches of dark green - olive patina - septum, shield hollow and lower blade; rest flaked and pocked to pale dirty green surface.
description: Dimensions: EL 128mm; EWe 52.3mm; MaxETse 25.5 mm (one corner); maxTsep 7.5mm; Wt 345.35 gms,Typology: curved sep. floor with rounded angles with fgs.; rounded sep.ends with very slight depression crossed by short vertical rib either face; fg. shape lost; st. prob. dipping in centre; shield hollow with deep centre on one blade face, poor surviving hollow on rev.; traces of cutting rib around; swelling on either side at blade top; flat blade faces,Manufacture: Portion of cg. fl. stump preserved in patina on one side; poss. edge bevel angle on corroded reverse face - but obverse flat despite surviving patina; skew between blade edge and sep.,Condition: much damaged - butt and all fg. crests broken pale green surs; as also rev. stop crest and most of blade edge; one blade tip ruddy brown break - recent dipping; most angles lost through deterioration,Attached Material: traces of fawn soil

collection: Nicklen,Mr. R. - Private,Charing Cross, Alderholt, Fordingbridge, Hants.
surface: Lower hald of one sep. with intact dark green patina; rest pock-scarred dull to pale green dry surface; dark brown with gold flecks on short blade tip; one fg. with bright gold stretch - mod. filing, others with odd gold fleck.
description: Dimensions: EL 121.5mm; EWe 43.3mm; EBfg. 20.7mm; minTst 17.8mm; maxTsep 6mm; Wt. 218.8 gms,Typology: single reasonably intact flange suggests broad loaf-shape; sep. floors almost flat crisp singles not fgs., rounded ends slightly undercutting step; slight constriction at bl. top, but no evidence for bars on sides; indication of shield rib design on blade faces - v. weak; lower blade into convex faces - poss. orig. midridge; 2 short ribs in base of one sep.,Manufacture: strong edge bevel but now diffuse due to deterioration; hints of cg. fl. in corroded surface; skewed cross-section probably due to mis-located values of mould,Condition: blade edge totally blunt; one blade tip short, rounded with no obvious break - possibly original form or anc. and/or corrosion wear; reverse fgs. very irregular with evidence for breaks - as also one obvious fg. with fractured part; all butt end broken.,Attached Material: Fawn soil in sep. and pocks
remarks: Metallurgy - Analyst: Craddock - Res. Lab. XRF determination - good tin - bronze with little lead (perhaps (1-2%)

publications: Wilts Arch. Mag. XLVI, p. 103-4. - Extract posted below,Devizes Museum cat. Part II, 2nd edition, page 70, Fig. 14,DM 1159; GC 353
remarks: Extract: "Bronze Dagger from Ashton Keynes. This bronze dagger was exhibited by the Rev. M. T. Milling during the Society's recent (1939) visit to the Church, and was most kindly presented by him then and there to the Society's Museum. "It was found," he writes, "by my clerk when digging a drock at North End, Ashton Keynes, twenty-three years ago. I looked to see at the time if there was anything else of interest in the spot dug, but I found nothing." The Society is indebted to Mr. A. D. Passmore for photographing both the dagger and the Roman objects mentioned in the preceding note. The dagger measures 6 ins. in length and 1 5/8 ins. width at the butt. It is in a remarkable state of preservation, the metal being quite uncorroded and showing yellow on one side and dark green on the other. The only injury is that a bit 3/4 in. wide in the centre of the butt which probably contained a third rivet hole is broken off, otherwise the weapon is perfect and the edges actually sharp enough still to cut a pencil with (I have just tried the experiment!). There is a prominent midrib on both sides and the edges are bevelled. A rare peculiarity is that the two rivet holes at the butt are not placed symmetrically. This perhaps rather suggests that it was a halberd blade, but it is too small for this. There is no specimen quite like it in the Society's collection. E.H. Goddard.
